hello-world/.body:
Hello World
TL;DR
You bootstrap an App Component to startup your app in the &lt;app&gt;
tag of your HTML.
index.html, main.ts, app.ts
index.html
Your main index.html file will be required to simply include the 
compiled and bundled version of your code and declare a tag that defines
the entry point of your app.
Something as empty and as simple as the following will work great:
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
  &lt;title&gt;Angular 2 StarWars Party!&lt;/title&gt;
      &lt;!--&lt;base&gt; is required for routing --&gt;
  &lt;base href=&quot;/&quot;&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;!-- &lt;app&gt; is the tag your Angular 2 app will be loaded into--&gt;
&lt;app&gt;
  Loading...
&lt;/app&gt;

&lt;!-- Place your script tag here. Often your build will inject it for you.--&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

app.ts
Your app.ts is your main application component.
The selector must match up with the &lt;app&gt; tag you used in your
index.html. If the selector is party-time, the tag would need to
be &lt;party-time&gt;&lt;/party-time&gt;.
The template is the main HTML of your project.
import {Component} from &apos;angular2/core&apos;;

@Component({
  selector: &apos;app&apos;,
  template:`
  Hello World!
`
})
export class App {}

The resulting body when run in the browser will look like the 
following. Notice how the Hello World is wrapped inside of an &lt;app&gt;
tag even though your main template does not have any tags:
&lt;body&gt;

&lt;app&gt;
  Hello World!
&lt;/app&gt;

&lt;script src=&quot;app.bundle.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;/body&gt;

main.ts
Import your App Component into your main.ts to bootstrap and 
startup your application. You can consider main.ts the entry point of 
your app and is only used for configuation and startup.
bootstrap returns a Promise, so you can use then and catch
to handle bootstrap completion or errors.
import {bootstrap} from &apos;angular2/platform/browser&apos;;
import {App} from &apos;./app&apos;;

bootstrap(App)
  .then(()=&gt; console.log(`App Running...`))
  .catch(err =&gt; console.log(err));

Show Me The Code
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
    &lt;meta charset=&quot;UTF-8&quot;&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Angular 2 App&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;base href=&quot;/&quot;&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;app&gt;&lt;/app&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

import {bootstrap} from &apos;angular2/platform/browser&apos;;
import {App} from &apos;./app&apos;;

bootstrap(App)
    .then(()=&gt; console.log(&apos;App running...&apos;))
    .catch(err =&gt; console.log(err));

import {Component} from &apos;angular2/core&apos;;

@Component({
    selector: &apos;app&apos;,
    template: `
        Hello! I&apos;m an App Container!
    `
})
export class App{}

What&apos;s That Syntax?
Import and Export (JavaScript)
import and export work together to help you share code between 
files.

export lets you expose the code you want to share
import lets you pull in the exported code

Assuming both of the files below are in the same directory:

foo.js
export var message = &quot;hi&quot;;

bar.js
import {message} from &apos;./foo&apos;;
console.log(message); //logs &quot;hi&quot;


Angular 2 Modules (JavaScript)
You will see many modules imported such as:

angular2/core
angular2/platform/browser
angular2/common

Just think of these as file paths to the code that you want to import.
Decorators (TypeScript)
@Component is a Decorator that changes the behavior of the class
defined directly underneath it.
Decorator() is really just a function that takes the object with 
{selector:&apos;app&apos;} and applies it. The @ simply links that function
to what&apos;s beneath it in the code. So when you see a Decorator think,
&quot;this is a function being invoked with what&apos;s declared next to it&quot;.
Classes (JavaScript)
The class keyword in JavaScript is just syntax sugar for what&apos;s been
done in JavaScript for years.
class Person{}
var person = new Person();

is the same as
function Person(){}
var person = new Person();
It&apos;s simply much shorter and easier to write:
class Person {
    constructor(message) {
        this.greeting = message;
    }
    greet() {
        return &quot;Hello, &quot; + this.greeting;
    }
}

than
function Person(message) {
        this.greeting = message;
    }
    Person.prototype.greet = function () {
        return &quot;Hello, &quot; + this.greeting;
    };

Classes create the same prototype chains we know from previous versions 
of JavaScript, but with an arguably saner syntax.
()=&gt; Arrow Functions
()=&gt; is used just like an anonymous function(){}, but it doesn&apos;t create a
this.
var sayHi = ()=&gt; console.log(&apos;hi&apos;);

is equivalent to:
var sayHi = function(){console.log(&apos;hi&apos;)};

If there&apos;s only one argument, you can actually omit the ():
var sayHi = message =&gt; console.log(message);

is equivalent to 
var sayHi = function(message){console.log(message)};

http/.body:
Loading Data with Http
TL;DR

Inject HTTP_PROVIDERS into your app providers
Inject Http into your Service
Use http.get() to define the request
Use an async pipe | async to &quot;subscribe&quot; to the request

Http
The http service is included in the angular2/http package. You
can actually use whatever http services you&apos;d like with Angular 2,
http is simply a convenience.
To use the http service, you&apos;ll need to include the HTTP_PROVIDERS
either in the same Component&apos;s providers:[] or in a parent 
Component&apos;s providers:[]. Typically, you&apos;d see the HTTP_PROVIDERS
in you App Component:
@Component({
    selector: &apos;app&apos;,
    providers: [HTTP_PROVIDERS], //Http is now available to children components
    template:`
        hi
    `
})
class App{}

Then in any child component (a &quot;smart&quot; one!) you&apos;d inject the Http service itself:
@Component({
    selector: `some-child-component`,
    template:`yo`
})
class SomeChildComponent{
    constructor(http:Http){
        //do http things
    }
}

http is built upon Observables. So when you call http.get(), 
it&apos;s not going to make the request until you subscribe to it.
//just sits there
http.get(&apos;http://localhost:4000&apos;)

//actually makes the request
http.get(&apos;http://localhost:4000&apos;).subscribe();

What this means is that you can define a request, assign it to a
variable/field/whatever, then subscribe to that variable.
const example = http.get(&apos;http://localhost:4000&apos;);

//pass &quot;example&quot; around, then subscribe
example.subscribe();

The Async Pipe | async
You can subscribe in a template with the | async. This means that 
you can make the assignment, pass it into the template, then render out
the results in the template whenenver the results are returned.
@Component({
    selector:&apos;example&apos;,
    template:`        
        {{people | async}}
    `
})
class Example{
    people;
    constructor(http:Http){
        this.people = http.get(&apos;http://localhost:4000/people&apos;);
    }
}

mapping the Response to JSON
Many services requests will return JSON objects, so any easy way to
get the JSON object is to map the response.
const example = http.get(&apos;http://localhost:4000&apos;)
    .map(res =&gt; res.json())

res.json() will grab the body as JSON and return it so you&apos;ll have
convenient access. map is an &quot;operator&quot; in RxJS, so to use it,
you&apos;ll need to import the map operator separately.
import &apos;rxjs/add/operator/map&apos;;

 Gotchas

Remember to import rxjs/add/operator/map when using get().map

Moving Http to a Service
To be able to share your various requests across your app, you
can move Http into its own Service:
@Injectable()
class ExampleService{
    people;
    constructor(http:Http){
        this.people = http.get(&apos;http://localhost:4000&apos;)
            .map(res =&gt; res.json())
    }
}

This way you can inject the Service into your Component (and any 
other Component for that matter):
@Component({
    selector: &apos;example-component&apos;,
    providers: [ExampleService],
    template: `
        {{exampleService.people | async}}
    `
})
class ExampleComponent{
    constructor(public exampleService:ExampleService){}
}

