@Injectable()
The @Injectable() decorator is required so that Angular 2 has the 
proper Metadata to be able to properly register your service with the 
Injector. You don&apos;t need to worry about the metadata, it&apos;s handled
during compilation from TypeScript to JavaScript. (This is also why 
&quot;emitDecoratorMetadata&quot;: true, is required in your tsconfig.json 
when compiling down your TypeScript.)
Importing vs. Injecting
It&apos;s easy to get confused between import and Injecting, but they&apos;re
not at all the same thing.
Importing (using the import keyword) is simply how JavaScript shares
code across files.
Injecting happens during &quot;runtime&quot; (when your application is running 
in the browser) and is how you share values/instances across your 
application.
What&apos;s That Syntax?
Async Pipe | async
While many pipes are used for formatting data, the Async Pipe is used
to allow data to be pushed into the template through either an 
Observable or a Promise.
The simplest example being a timer:
import {Component} from &apos;angular2/core&apos;;
