import &apos;rxjs/add/observable/interval&apos;;
@Component({
    selector: &apos;home&apos;,
    template: `
        {{timer | async}}
    `
})
export class Home{
    timer = Observable.interval(1000)
}

injecting-services/.body:
Injecting Services
TL;DR

Services are usually classes
Services are injected into providers: []
Injecting into bootstrap is meant to &quot;override&quot; other injections
Inject into &quot;Smart&quot; components, not &quot;Dumb&quot; ones

Injecting Services
You can provide anything you need into your Angular 2 application,
but you&apos;ll typically be injecting Services as classes. You mark
your Service with the @Injectable() decorator, add it to the
smart component&apos;s providers:[] where you&apos;ll need it, then inject
it into the constructor of the Component where it will be used.
Create a Service
Open a new file, create a class, done . Something as simple
as the following will work just fine:
export class ExampleService{
    message = &quot;hi&quot;;
}

Decorate Your Service with @Injectable()
The @Injectable() decorator is required so that Angular 2 has the 
proper Metadata to be able to properly register your service with the 
Injector. You don&apos;t need to worry about the metadata, it&apos;s handled
during compilation from TypeScript to JavaScript. (This is also why 
&quot;emitDecoratorMetadata&quot;: true, is required in your tsconfig.json 
when compiling down your TypeScript.)
@Injectable()
export class ExampleService{
    message = &quot;hi&quot;;
}

Provide Your Service to a Smart Component
Each @Component decorator has a providers:[] array where you place
the classes you want to inject.
To provide your ExampleService to an App Component:
@Component({
    selector: &apos;app&apos;,
    providers: [ExampleService],
    template: `I&apos;m an App Component`
})
class App{}

Inject Into the Constructor of the Smart Component
The last step before you can actually use the Service is to inject it
into the constructor of the Component.
@Component({
    selector: &apos;app&apos;,
    providers: [ExampleService],
    template: `Hi`
})
class App{
    constructor(exampleService:ExampleService){
        console.log(exampleService.message); //logs &quot;hi&quot;
    }
}

This ExampleService will now be available to this component and all
its children components. Remember, services are injected into &quot;smart&quot;
components. If you need a value from the service in a &quot;dumb&quot; component,
inject the service into a smart component, then use an @Input() on the
&quot;dumb&quot; component:
@Component({
    selector:&apos;dumb&apos;,
    template: `
        {{message}} &lt;-- &quot;hi&quot;
    `
})
class Dumb{
    @Input message;
}

@Component({
    selector: &apos;smart&apos;,
    providers: [ExampleService],
    directives: [Dumb],
    template:`&lt;dumb [message]=&quot;exampleService.message&quot;&gt;&lt;/dumb&gt;`
})
class SmartComponent{
    constructor(public exampleService:ExampleService){}
}

