pipes/.body:
Pipes
TL;DR

Decorate a class with @Pipe
name your pipe
Add a transform method to your pipe
transform is invoked with (input, arg1, arg2, etc)
Return whatever output you&apos;d like from the pipe
Include the pipe in your Component pipes:[]
Use your pipe in the template {{data | myPipe:arg1:arg2}} 

Pipes
If you&apos;re coming from Angular 1, you&apos;ll soon notice the lack of
a filter pipe and others that you may have come to rely on.
Fortunately, pipes are extremely easy to create and share. Personally,
I expect a large library of reusable Angular 2 pipes to be coming in 
the future.
| json Pipe
The | json pipe is extremely helpful for debugging in templates.
{{myObject | json}}

Built-in Formatting Pipes
| date, | uppercase, | lowercase, | currency, | percent are
all available to format your template expressions:
{{ birthday | date:&quot;MM/dd/yy&quot; }}

Chaining Pipes
Pipes can be used one after the other. The output of the previous pipe 
will be used as the input for the next:
&lt;!-- Results in something like &quot;MONDAY, MAY 2, 2016 --&gt;
{{ birthday | date | uppercase}}

Custom Pipes
You create a custom pipe using a @Pipe() decorator on a class.
The @Pipe() requires a name, then you simply create a transform
method that will take your template variable as input, then output
whatever you return. Often, you&apos;re either formatting a string or 
manipulating an array.
Show Me the Code
import {Pipe} from &apos;angular2/core&apos;;
@Pipe({
  name: &apos;search&apos;
})
export class Search{
  transform(data, key, term = &quot;&quot;){
    if(!data) return null;
    return data.filter(item =&gt; {
      return item[key].toLowerCase().includes(term.toLowerCase());
    })
  }
}

@Component({
  selector: &apos;person-list&apos;,
  directives: [Card],
  //include your pipe
  pipes:[Search],
  template: `
&lt;input [(ngModel)]=&quot;name&quot; type=&quot;text&quot;&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;card-container&quot;&gt;
  &lt;card
    &lt;!-- use your pipe --&gt;
    *ngFor=&quot;#person of people | search:&apos;name&apos;:name&quot;
    [person]=&quot;person&quot;&gt;
  &lt;/card&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
`
})
export class PersonList{}

routing/.body:
Routing
TL;DR

Routing is very configuration heavy, be patient 
Configure routes for your components by decorating with @RouteConfig
Define routes like {path: &apos;/party&apos;, name: &apos;Party&apos;, component: Party}
The router loads a component into the &lt;router-outlet&gt;
Route to a name with [routerLink]=&quot;[&apos;Party&apos;]&quot;
You build routes in a confusing array syntax: [routerLink]=&quot;[&apos;/ChildItem&apos;, {id: &apos;someId&apos;}, &apos;SubItem1&apos;, {itemName: &apos;someName&apos;}]

&lt;base href=&quot;/&quot;&gt;
Don&apos;t forget to include this in the &lt;head&gt; of your index.html, or else routing
won&apos;t know where to start:
  &lt;base href=&quot;/&quot;&gt;

@RouteConfig()
With @RouteConfig() your App Component basically becomes a target
for where the router will render components.
So an App component will typically have:

Navigation
&lt;router-outlet&gt; (where your components are loaded)
Header/Footer/etc

Decorator your App component with your root routes so that when your
application loads, it knows which components to load. Loading a Home
component would look like:
  @Component({
    //selector, template, etc
  })
  @RouteConfig([
    {path: &apos;/home&apos;, name: &apos;Home&apos;, component: Home, useAsDefault: true}   
  ])
  export class App{}

 Gotcha
Notice how the App is decorated with both @Component AND @RouteConfig.
The nature of decorators allows you to stack them one on top of the other as long
as the code immediately following is something that can be decorated, e.g. a class.
&lt;router-outlet&gt;
Now you need somewhere to render out your Home component.
Compare using the Home component as a directive:
  @Component({
        //selector, etc
        directives: [Home],
        template:`
            &lt;home&gt;&lt;/home&gt;
        `
  })
  export class App{}

Vs. loading the Home component as a route:
  @Component({
    //selector, etc
        template:`
            &lt;router-outlet&gt;&lt;/router-outlet&gt;
        `
  })
  @RouteConfig([
    {path: &apos;/home&apos;, name: &apos;Home&apos;, component: Home, useAsDefault: true}   
  ])
  export class App{}

[routerLink]
Using [routerLink] directive allows you to hook into the routing system
from your template. To navigate to your Home component, you add a
[routerLink] that looks like the following:
&lt;a [routerLink]=&quot;[&apos;Home&apos;]&quot;&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;

.router-link-active
.router-link-active is a style that is automatically applied added to
an element with [routerLink] defined when that link is active. This is
great for highlighting in navigation.
And Beyond...
Going in-depth into router is outside the scope of this workshop, but
the general gist through code samples:
  @RouteConfig([
    //&quot;...&quot; allows &quot;children&quot;
    {path: &apos;/person/...&apos;, name: &apos;Person&apos;, component: Person}   
  ])

//The Person component would *also* have a `@RouteConfig()` to handle its children 
@RouteConfig([    
    // the &quot;/&quot; signifies a &quot;terminal&quot; route. These are required so the route 
    //at least stops somewhere
    {path: &apos;/detail/&apos;, name: &apos;Detail&apos;, component: Detail}   
  ])
export class Person{}

A param in a route:
 { path: &apos;/person/:id/&apos;, component: Person, name: &apos;Person&apos; },

Matches up with a param in a constructor:
constructor(params: RouteParams) {    
    this.id = params.get(&apos;id&apos;);
}

The router has &quot;lifecycle hook&quot; decorators to allow or prevent navigation:
@CanActivate, @OnActivate, @CanDeactivate
//Takes a function invoked with the &quot;next&quot; route and the &quot;previous&quot; route.
//Return a boolean or a Promise that resolves to a boolean.
@CanActivate((next, prev) =&gt; boolean | Promise&lt;boolean&gt;)

smart-and-dumb-components/.body:
Smart and Dumb Components
TL;DR
Smart Components

Specific to your App
Are Containers for Dumb Components
Handle passing Data around (covered later)
Handle routing (covered later)
Use providers:[]

Dumb Components

Are reusable across apps
Use @Input() to receive data from the container
@Input() foo; is handled by [foo]=&quot;bar&quot; in the container 
Use @Output() to push data out to the container
@Output() is a new EventEmitter which emit() data out
@Output() foo = new EventEmitter(); is triggered with foo.emit() 
then handled by (foo)=&quot;onFoo()&quot; in the container

Smart Components
There&apos;s only one Component, but some Components are
specific to your application while others are going to be reusable.
We&apos;ll call a Component that&apos;s specific to your application a
&quot;smart&quot; component. This means that your routes, data, and application
wiring would all hook together using these types of Component. In
practice, this means that &quot;smart&quot; Component use providers:[] for
hooking up your application into the Component. 
These Components also load in &quot;dumb&quot; Components, so their templates will
typically be larger and have a few &quot;dumb&quot; components listed in their
directives array.
Dumb Components
A reusable Component is a &quot;dumb&quot; Component. This Component shouldn&apos;t 
know anything about your application. No routes. No services. Nothing 
application specific.
All data in dumb Components should be passed in through @Input(). All
data going out should be pushed out with @Output(). Using providers:[]
in &quot;dumb&quot; components is rare and never used for application data.
